        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">ᚅᚓᚈᚐᚉᚐᚏᚔ</name> <space unit="stroke" quantity="1"/> <name nymRef="#?">ᚅᚓᚈᚐᚉᚐ<unclear reason="worn">ᚌᚔ</unclear></name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/><persName><name nymRef="#?">NETACARI</name> <space unit="stroke" quantity="1"/> <name nymRef="#?">NETACA<unclear reason="worn">GI</unclear></name></persName>
                </ab>
               <!-- <ab type="list"></ab>-->
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>There appears to be a slight space between the -I of NETA-CARI and the N of the following name.</note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>'of Nad Cair of Nad Caige (?)'</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>NET(T)A 'champion' (later falling together with NIOT(T)A 'sister's son' when both became <distinct xml:lang="sga"><ref target="https://dil.ie/33151">Nad</ref></distinct>-) is frequently found as an element in personal/kin group names (eg. NETA-SEGAMONAS on (I-WAT-002) Ardmore I and (I-WAT-042) Island). In this case, the NETA spelling would suggest the word meaning 'champion', rather than NIOT(T)A, which can be used alone as a formula word meaning 'sister's son' (cf. (I-KER-124) Gurrane, Co. Kerry).</p>
            </div>
